\cb3 Types of Orders\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa238\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 Market Order**
\f1\b0 \cf5 \cb3 \strokec5 \'a0\'96 An order to buy or sell immediately at the best price currently available in the market. Market orders are popular for traders who want to buy or sell without delay. However, a market order does not guarantee a price; it only assures an immediate execution. The last-traded price is not necessarily the price at which the market order will be filled. In highly volatile market conditions, it is possible a market order will be filled away from the last-traded price.\cf5 \cb1 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa293\partightenfactor0

\fs34\fsmilli17290 \cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 Example: When placing a buy order on the EUR/USD at the current ask price of 1.2050, a market order is placed for a long position in the EUR/USD at the best price available in the market. A market order does not guarantee a price. It only has immediate execution.**\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa238\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 Entry Order**\'a0
\f1\b0 \cf5 \cb3 \strokec5 \'96 An order to buy or sell when a specific price is reached and remains in effect until the client cancels the order. There are 4 types of Entry Orders:\cf5 \cb1 \strokec5 \
